{
  "texts": [
    "Surface GeometryThe surfaces L(H, V), T (H, V), C(H, V), and K(H, V) collectively create a geometric structure resembling valleys and ridges:• L decreases along V but increases along H, • T increases but saturates with H and V, • C increases linearly with H and superlinearly with V, • K grows with H and shrinks with V. Key Insight: The minimum of F is rarely on the axisaligned edges (pure scale-up or pure scale-out).",
    "Instead, minima lie inside the plane, along diagonal trajectories.",
    "Diagonal scaling refers to coordinated changes in H and V. We now provide a deeper theoretical justification.",
    "Scaling TrajectoriesConsider a trajectory:τ (t) = (H(t), V (t)),where both H and V increase with t. Let m = dH d∥V ∥ be the slope.Goal: Find m * minimizing:F (H(t), V (t)).",
    "B. Gradient Alignment ConditionThe gradient of F is:∇F = ∂F ∂H, ∂F ∂∥V ∥.A local optimum along a trajectory direction (1, m) is reached when:∇F (H *, V *) • (1, m *) = 0.Thus the optimal diagonal direction (1, m *) aligns with -∇F."
  ]
}